managing-dhcp-759.md:* [What are reserved IP ranges?](/t/concepts-and-terms/785#heading--ip-ranges)
managing-dhcp-759.md:* [What is post-commission configuration](/t/commission-nodes/822#heading--post-commission-configuration)
managing-dhcp-759.md:* [How and why should I enable MAAS-managed DHCP?](/t/managing-dhcp/759#heading--enabling-dhcp)
managing-dhcp-759.md:* [How do I resolve IP conflicts?](/t/managing-dhcp/759#heading--resolving-ip-conflicts)
managing-dhcp-759.md:* [How can I extend a reserved dynamic IP range?](/t/managing-dhcp/759#heading--extending-a-reserved-dynamic-ip-range)
managing-dhcp-759.md:* [How and why should I configure external  DHCP?](/t/managing-dhcp/759#heading--external-dhcp-and-a-reserved-ip-range)
managing-dhcp-759.md:* [How and why should I use a DHCP relay?](/t/managing-dhcp/759#heading--dhcp-relay)
managing-dhcp-759.md:* [How and why should I customize MAAS with DHCP snippets?](/t/managing-dhcp/759#heading--dhcp-snippets)
managing-dhcp-759.md:MAAS-managed DHCP needs a reserved dynamic IP range enlist and commission machines. You should create such a range when you are enabling DHCP with the web UI. See [MAAS CLI](/t/common-cli-tasks/794#heading--enable-dhcp) for instructions for doing this with the CLI.
managing-dhcp-759.md:If necessary, it is possible to add further portions of the subnet to the dynamic IP range (see [IP ranges](/t/ip-ranges/760)). Furthermore, since you enabled DHCP on a VLAN basis and a VLAN can contain multiple subnets, it is possible to add a portion from those subnets as well. Just select the subnet under the 'Subnets' page and reserve a dynamic range. DHCP will be enabled automatically.
managing-dhcp-759.md:If an external DHCP server is used to deploy machines, then a reserved IP range should be created to prevent the address namespace from being corrupted. For instance, address conflicts may occur if you set a machine's IP assignment mode to 'Auto assign' in the context of an external DHCP server. See [IP ranges](/t/ip-ranges/760) to create such a range. It should correspond to the lease range of the external server.
managing-dhcp-759.md:2.  Set up the external relay. This relay is set up independently from MAAS. See [DHCP relay](/t/concepts-and-terms/785#heading--dhcp-relay) for software suggestions.
managing-dhcp-759.md:3.  Configure MAAS-managed DHCP. Navigate to the source VLAN page and select the 'Relay DHCP' action. Fill in the fields in the resulting form. The crucial setting is the target VLAN ('Relay VLAN'). Press the 'Relay DHCP' button to finish. See [MAAS CLI](/t/advanced-cli-tasks/793#heading--relay-dhcp) for how to do this with the CLI.
managing-dhcp-759.md:See [MAAS CLI](/t/cli-dhcp-snippet-management/796) for doing this with the CLI.
network-discovery-758.md:MAAS constantly listens to the network and reports any discovered devices. Devices are identified when the rack controller observes them communicating on an attached IPv4 subnet. Discovered devices that do not correspond to machines and devices already known to MAAS are shown on the [Dashboard](/t/web-ui/782#heading--maas-dashboard). If a device advertises a hostname using `mDNS` (such as with `avahi` or `Bonjour`), MAAS will also present the discovered hostname in the Dashboard.
network-testing-1267.md:* [How do I use network link testing?](/t/network-testing/1267#heading--network-link-testing)
